            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1521158801,
            "creation_date": 1521158801,
            "body": "<p>There's limitation to <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs/concepts/limits\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Google Datastore<\/a>. The official recommendation is to split up your large entity into a logical <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/appengine/docs/standard/python/datastore/entities#Python_Kinds_and_identifiers\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Entity group<\/a> with ancestors and their children defined.<\/p>\n\n<p>Think of it like nested records. If you create an entity called \"Employees\", you can create children entities like \"Performance\" and \"Profile\". This way you don't need that employee's entire history and profile in one entity.<\/p>\n\n<p>Basically, you can design your datastore structure to ensure each individual entity do not exceed 1MB in size.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 49311256,
            "question_id": 49262879
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/C23OI.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1787583,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1628715,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1628715/rmrf",
                "reputation": 133,
                "display_name": "rmrf"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1521313913,
            "creation_date": 1521313913,
            "body": "<p>Currently, each unindexed String property can be <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/appengine/docs/standard/go/datastore/entity-property-reference\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">up to 1MB<\/a>, and total entity size 1MB. The \"Limits\" doc in the comment on OP was updated to use this value.<\/p>\n\n<p>Entity groups can be a solution here.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 49340870,
            "question_id": 49262879
        }
